{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658940"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20841"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20841"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96405"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79054"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12664"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96405"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the comprehensive cellular effects of MYC overexpression in cancer cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Selective activation of cell cycle checkpoint proteins","Coordinated upregulation of growth and metabolic programs","Specific inhibition of apoptotic signalling pathways","Exclusive promotion of angiogenesis via VEGF induction","Direct suppression of tumour suppressor gene expression"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoordinated upregulation of growth and metabolic programs\u003C/strong\u003E. MYC functions as a master transcriptional regulator that simultaneously controls multiple cellular processes essential for rapid cancer cell growth. These include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDirect activation of cell cycle regulators such as D cyclins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUpregulation of ribosomal RNA genes and rRNA processing to enhance protein synthesis capacity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMetabolic reprogramming through increased expression of glycolytic enzymes and factors involved in glutamine metabolism (contributing to the Warburg effect)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGeneration of metabolic intermediates needed for macromolecule synthesis (DNA, proteins, lipids)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUpregulation of telomerase in some contexts, contributing to cellular immortalization\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPromotion of cancer cell stemness, enhancing tumour immortality\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective activation of cell cycle checkpoint proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - While MYC does activate some cell cycle proteins like D cyclins, its effects are much broader than just cell cycle regulation and it typically overrides rather than activates checkpoints.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecific inhibition of apoptotic signalling pathways\u003C/strong\u003E - MYC can actually sensitize cells to apoptosis under certain conditions; its primary function is not apoptosis inhibition but rather growth promotion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExclusive promotion of angiogenesis via VEGF induction\u003C/strong\u003E - While MYC may indirectly influence angiogenesis, this is not its primary or exclusive function.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect suppression of tumour suppressor gene expression\u003C/strong\u003E - MYC primarily functions as a transcriptional activator rather than a repressor of tumour suppressor genes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe comprehensive effects of MYC on multiple cellular processes explain why tumours with high MYC expression, such as Burkitt lymphoma, demonstrate exceptionally rapid growth rates.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MYC functions as a master transcriptional regulator that controls multiple cellular processes including cell growth, metabolism, and ribosome biogenesis.","MYC upregulates genes involved in metabolic reprogramming, particularly glycolytic enzymes and glutamine metabolism, contributing to the Warburg effect in cancer cells.","MYC contributes to cancer cell immortalization through multiple mechanisms including telomerase upregulation and promotion of cancer cell stemness."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 289-290."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79054"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79054"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T11:15:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T11:15:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13716"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96405"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1159